      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, thanks for telling me about this — sharp knee pain for two weeks is genuinely worth taking seriously, and I'm glad you're not just pushing through without saying something.\n\nI have to be straight with you here: diagnosing what's causing that pain is outside my lane as a coach. Sharp pain that's lasted two weeks, gets worse on stairs, and started after a hard effort — that's a conversation for a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor, not a running coach. They can actually examine your knee, figure out what's going on, and give you a real answer. That's what you deserve here, not a guess from me.\n\nOn the ibuprofen question specifically — that's also one for a medical professional. There are real considerations around using anti-inflammatories before exercise, and a doctor is the right person to weigh in on that for your situation.\n\nI know it's frustrating to hear \"see a professional\" when you just want to know if it's okay to keep running. But here's the honest reality: if I tell you to shorten your runs and the underlying issue is something that needs rest or treatment, I could be steering you toward something that sets you back much further. Your half marathon is on July 11th — **you have time**, and protecting that window matters more than squeezing in kilometers right now.\n\n---\n\n**What I *can* do** is hold your training plan steady and be ready to adapt it the moment you have some clarity from a medical professional. Once you know what you're working with, we can figure out together what modified training looks like — whether that's cross-training to maintain your aerobic base, adjusting your build timeline, or something else entirely. A two-week pause now, handled well, doesn't have to derail what you're building toward.\n\n**The next step I'd suggest:** Book that physio or sports medicine appointment as soon as you can — ideally this week. \n\nWhen you have an answer, come back and we'll make a plan together. What does your access to a sports medicine professional look like — is that something you can get to relatively easily?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01Sk9LwKcUbgsbZYbUDUCbUY"
    }
